{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17507497","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17507497"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:53:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:53:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2631"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2631","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2631"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.2,0.06,0.64,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2631"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44013"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2631","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2631"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2631"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28994"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1075"},{"type":"tags","id":"3496"},{"type":"tags","id":"4932"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2969"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10757"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42532"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44355"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44013","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/44013"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA six-year-old boy is brought to the Emergency Department by his mother with a papular erythematous eruption across most of his body. She reports he has been scratching for the last week. He is not sleeping due to the itch and is struggling to concentrate at school however otherwise been feeling systemically well. He has a history of eczema but his mother reports it has never been this extensive before. They live in a house with 12 occupants in total over three generations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, his vital parameters are within normal limits. There are multiple excoriated erythematous papules, predominantly in acral sites. On examination of the web spaces with dermoscopy you notice the characteristic \u0027delta sign\u0027 and the \u2018jet with contrail pattern\u2019. There are several areas of the patients skin that appear to be secondarily infected.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following statements would be appropriate patient education regarding this skin condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Treatment of the affected individual is generally adequate to stop the spread of disease","Permethrin cream should be applied to the affected areas of the body, as required","Fumigation is required","This disease is extremely contagious","Rash and pruritis persisting for one week after treatment should be reviewed by a Dermatologist."],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical history and examination is suggestive of scabies infestation. \u003Cstrong\u003EScabies is an extremely contagious condition\u003C/strong\u003E. \u003Cstrong\u003EAll household members and close contacts\u003C/strong\u003E of the affected individual should be treated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPermethrin cream should be applied to the affected areas of the body, as required \u003C/strong\u003Eis not correct as permethrin should be applied to the whole body except the face, and not in an \u0027as required\u0027 manner. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETreatment options for scabies include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Col\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETopical permethrin 5% cream to the whole body (except the face) for a minimum of eight hours (usually overnight). Care should be taken to apply the cream to hands and genitalia and also underneath the fingernails. Treatment should be repeated in seven days.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFirst line treatment for adults and children over the age of six months\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETopical benzyl benzoate 25% emulsion to whole body (except the face) for 24 hours. Care should be taken to apply the cream to hands and genitalia and also underneath the fingernails. Treatment should be repeated in seven days.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf patient allergic to permethrin or if permethrin treatment fails\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOral ivermectin (adult and child 15 kg or more) 200 micrograms/kg orally with fatty food, once weekly until scrapings from a burrow are negative and there is no further clinical evidence of infestation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf infestation resistant to topical treatment, issues with compliance of topical treatment, for crusted scabies, in institutionalised/overcrowded settings\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ol\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFumigation is not required.\u003C/strong\u003E Clothing, towels and bedding should be washed on a hot cycle. Items that cannot be washed should be stored in a sealed plastic bag for eight days.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESymptoms usually resolve within a few days of completing treatment, however the \u003Cstrong\u003Erash and pruritis may take four to six weeks\u003C/strong\u003E to resolve.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Scabies is an extremely contagious infestation.","First line treatment for scabies is topical permethrin 5% cream to the whole body, excluding the face."],"references":["Thomas C, Coates SJ, Engelman D, Chosidow O, Chang AY. Ectoparasites: Scabies. J Am Acad Dermatol. 2020;82(3):533-548. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31310840/","Hardy M, Engelman D, Steer A. Scabies: A clinical update. Aust Fam Physician. 2017;46(5):264-268. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2017/may/scabies-a-clinical-update"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28994"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2631"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28994","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/28994"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-04-04T16:04:39+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-04-04T16:04:39+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2631"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44013"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/t